%N A390402 a(n) is the smallest k > 1 such that n^k reaches n under repeated application of the Collatz or 3x+1 map (A006370), or a(n) = -1 if no such k exists.
%C A390402 a(n) = -1 when n is a multiple of 3, since in that case only starting x = n*2^i can reach n, and such an x is never of the form n^k.
%C A390402 Empirical observations suggest a(n) != -1 otherwise, i.e. a(A001651(n)) > 1.
%C A390402 Pure numbers (A061641) have the least probability to reach the value 2 in this sequence. Yet the only known case is a(7).
%C A390402 Has a(n)/n any bound?
%H A390402 <a href="/index/3#3x1">Index entries for sequences related to 3x+1 (or Collatz) problem</a>
%F A390402 a(3*n) = -1.
%F A390402 a(2^n) = 2.
%o A390402 (PARI)
%o A390402 isin(m, n) = while(m!=1&&m!=n, if(m%2==0, m=m/2, m=m*3+1)); (m==n);
%o A390402 a(n) = if(n%3==0, return(-1), my(k=2); while(isin(n^k, n)==0, k++); return(k))
